  "response": "Paranitrophenol is more acidic than phenol.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Resonance Stabilization:** Both phenol and paranitrophenol can stabilize the phenoxide ion (the conjugate base formed after deprotonation) through resonance. This delocalization of the negative charge makes the phenoxide ion more stable, driving the equilibrium towards deprotonation and thus increasing acidity.\n\n*   **Electron-Withdrawing Effect of the Nitro Group:** The nitro group (-NO2) is a strong electron-withdrawing group. When it is located at the para position of phenol (paranitrophenol), it has a significant inductive and resonance effect on the phenoxide ion. This electron-withdrawing effect further stabilizes the negative charge on the phenoxide ion, making it *much* more stable than the phenoxide ion formed from phenol alone. This increased stability greatly favors the formation of the conjugate base and thus increases the acidity.\n\nIn summary, the nitro group in paranitrophenol provides extra stability to the conjugate base compared to phenol, making paranitrophenol the more acidic compound.\n",
